[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering environment variable setup**\n\nI'm thinking about how to set up environment variables for testing new 3.0 arrays. It's tricky since they can't be set after generation. Maybe the agent guidance suggests setting them in test via SystemLambda, but I want to avoid adding extra dependencies. Java's reflection hack feels like a bad idea. While environment variable coverage is important, actual testing may not need them for core coverage. I might need to test System properties as they’re easier.\n\n**Evaluating agent guidance**\n\nI’m deciding on how to give agent guidance regarding using built-in .properties or MapPropertySource. I need to isolate environment and system properties by adjusting System properties. What action should we take? If there's no deterministic setup, the guidance might just suggest advisory preparation, maybe no action if no extra setup is required. I should consider if optional modules like \"hoplite-yaml\" would be useful, but mainly focus on whether additional dependencies are truly needed to achieve meaningful coverage.\n\n**Analyzing properties classpath**\n\nI’m considering using the properties classpath resource without needing an extra module. It seems like focusing on exercise parsers with ConfigLoaderBuilder.default and using data class reflection could provide more meaningful results than just sticking to the scaffold, and without adding any dependencies. I’m wondering if some optional modules could require cloud services or Docker, but that doesn't seem core to the task. I might need to inspect module metadata to ensure there are no unnecessary service clients involved.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_09371b1bd2552211016a41b4a685f88190bc1b3421a33fa947\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqQbSvm9kqC4NmJ7ET5Z_zI5y7wlKFc0UQwb4NVDb2EJODjOtTl9YfBqXZLB56ipNqzaS8WXK3O6nzWbh-PFeWMfoI